# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apples-and-honey
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] Jewish women of New York City staged a boycott of kosher butchers in 1902 in response to a coordinated increase in price of kosher meat from 12 to 18 cents a pound.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] This increase was significant enough that many Jewish families could no longer afford to buy meat.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] The protests, led mainly by immigrant Jewish women on Manhattan's Lower East Side, though controversial in their often-violent tactics, were largely successful and resulted in the lowering of the price of meat to 14 cents a pound.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] The kosher meat boycott of 1902 developed as the Gilded Age was coming to a close.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] The Gilded Age (1870–1900) in the United States saw powerful robber barons monopolizing a wide array of industries including the railroad, oil, steel and meat industries.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] These monopolies and trusts were able to dramatically increase prices in their respective industries, and prevented consumers from finding goods at a cheaper price.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] Though Congress passed a number of antitrust laws in the 1890s, such as the Sherman Antitrust Act, these laws were not usually enforced and the government often sided with the powerful robber barons.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] At the turn of the 20th century, the meat industry was still under the control of robber barons who in 1902 decided to hike prices.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] Initially, the Jewish butchers in New York City attempted to boycott the meat trust by refusing to sell meat, but the trust was too powerful and their boycott crumbled.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] Thus the women of the Lower East Side Jewish community were forced to take matters into their own hands, staging a large boycott and convincing many people not to buy meat.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] These protests took place at a time when women were beginning to exert political influence.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] In addition to the rise of women's suffrage movements, the end of the 19th century saw the number of middle class American women volunteering in clubs, professional societies, and local charities increase significantly.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] This trend in turn lent much more strength to women's suffrage movements and provided a model for women to exert their influence in other areas, such as in the kosher meat boycott.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] In general, kosher meat tends to be pricier than non-kosher meat due to the various restrictions and requirements that come with it.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] Adhering to the strict dietary laws of *kashrut* is a significant part of Orthodox Jewish life.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] The laws of *kashrut* can be found throughout the Torah, Mishnah, Talmud and various halachic works.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] The main criteria for a mammal to be kosher is that the animal must have split hooves and chew its cud.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] Additionally, a certified butcher known as a shochet must slaughter the animal in accordance with Jewish law in a process known as shechita.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] After the shechita, the animal must be checked for any life-threatening wounds which could render the animal not kosher even after being properly slaughtered.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] Finally many parts of the animal have to be removed such as certain fats and all the blood.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] The meat is then salted in order to remove any remaining blood.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] This lengthy process and the many steps involved are what make kosher meat more expensive than non-kosher meat.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] In 1902 the kosher meat was recorded to be 5-6 cents more expensive per pound than non-kosher meat, even before the price increased.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] In 1902, although many American Jews began to assimilate and drop many of their religious practices, many still kept kosher.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] Because of this, the increase in price for kosher meat had a relatively widespread impact.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] On May 11, 1902, around 400 kosher butchers on the East Side of New York organized a boycott of the meat trusts to put pressure on them to lower the cost of meat.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] However, the trusts were too powerful and the butchers ended their boycott.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] In response to those unsuccessful attempts, the women of the Lower East Side Jewish community, led by Fanny Levy and Sarah Edelson, held a massive protest.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] On May 15, 20,000 protesters, mostly women, took to the streets to attack the butcher shops.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] They smashed shop windows, poured gasoline on the meat, lit it on fire and threw pieces of meat at police officers.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] By the end of the day, 85 people had been arrested, 75% of them women.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] After May 15, the protests expanded into local synagogues.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] During Sabbath services on May 17, two days after the street riots, a group of women stormed the podium of their synagogue to direct attention towards their cause.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] One woman got up on the synagogue podium, disrupted the Torah reading and lectured the community about the importance of joining the boycott.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] She then demanded that the men in the community compel their wives to join the protestors.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] The strategy of promoting the boycott inside synagogues gained much attention and proved to be an effective means of gaining support within the Jewish community.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] In the weeks following the riots, Jewish women of the Lower East Side continued to come up with creative ways to protest.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] They patrolled the streets of the Lower East Side in order to prevent other women from buying meat.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] In a controversial but effective move, the protesters went door to door checking everyone's pots and pans to ensure that no one was secretly buying meat.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] Anyone who was caught with meat was ridiculed and labeled a "scab." These tactics proved to be very effective.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] Almost all purchases of kosher meats ceased.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] While the patrols went on, other boycott members worked around the clock to disseminate flyers and circulars in order to bolster support.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] One such circular read: "Eat no meat while the Trust is taking meat from the bones of your women and children." Women vigilantes went as far as to rob butcher shops and rid them of their meat.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] The women involved in the protests also started a fundraising campaign to bail out imprisoned boycotters.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] Due to the boycott's successful tactics, on May 22, the Retail Butchers Association (the kosher butchers association) realigned itself with the boycott campaign and ceased selling kosher meat in all their stores.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] In addition, kosher restaurants throughout NYC removed meat from their menus until the prices came back down.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] By May 27, major Orthodox religious leaders had publicly affirmed support for the boycott, and by June 9 the prices dropped to 14 cents a pound.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] Newspapers across NYC had many different reactions to the boycott.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] *The Forward*, a Yiddish newspaper, endorsed the boycott by praising them with a newspaper title "Bravo, Bravo, Bravo, Jewish women!" Many Jewish socialists were also sympathetic to the boycott.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] *The Tribune* also denounced the method of protesting, stating that the boycotters "made life miserable for the policemen." Ida Tarbell and Lincoln Steffens, two muckraker journalists, were pleased with the boycott's exposure of the robber barons and their corrupt policies.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] The *New York Herald* came out with an article portraying the event as testimony to the impressive organizational skills of the women who put together the boycott.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] The boycott became so popular that its influence eventually spread to other Jewish communities in Harlem, Brooklyn, Newark, Boston, and Philadelphia, where similar protests took place.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] Many of the women who organized the kosher meat boycott of 1902 as well as their children played a significant role in the New York Labor movement, most notably the garment labor union.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] In 1907 and 1908 rent boycotts broke out on the lower east side of Manhattan to protest high rent prices.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] They publicly acknowledged that the inspiration for the boycott and the tactics used derived from the meat boycott of 1902.
[src:apples-and-honey/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] In 1910, a meat boycott also occurred across the US primarily the Midwest, in part likely inspired by the 1902 kosher boycott.
[src:apples-and-honey/abudaraho] The English name, *bottarga*, was borrowed from Italian.
[src:apples-and-honey/abudaraho] The Italian form is thought to have been introduced from the Arabic *buṭarḫah* (بطارخة), plural form *buṭariḫ* (‏بطارخ‎), itself from Byzantine Greek ᾠοτάριχον (*oiotárikhon*), a combination of the words ᾠόν ('egg') and τάριχον ('pickled').
[src:apples-and-honey/abudaraho] 1500, as the Greek form of the word, when transliterated into Latin as *ova tarycha*, occurs in Bartolomeo Platina's *De honesta voluptate* (c.
[src:apples-and-honey/abudaraho] In an Italian manuscript that "closely parallels" Platina's cookbook and dated to shortly after its publication, *botarghe* is attested in the corresponding passage.
[src:apples-and-honey/abudaraho] The first mention of the Greek form (*oiotárikhon*) occurs in the 11th century, in the writings of Simeon Seth, who denounced the food as something to be "avoided totally", although a similar phrase may have been in use since antiquity in the same denotation.
[src:apples-and-honey/abudaraho] It has been suggested that the Coptic *outarakhon* may be an intermediate form between the Greek and Arabic, whereas examination of dialectical variants of the Greek ᾠόν 'egg' includes the Pontic Greek ὠβόν (traditionally where the mullets are caught), and ὀβό or βό in parts of Asia Minor.
[src:apples-and-honey/abudaraho] The modern Greek name comes from the Byzantine Greek, substituting the modern word αυγό for the ancient word ᾠóν.
[src:apples-and-honey/abudaraho] Bottarga production is first documented in the Nile Delta in the 10th century BCE.
[src:apples-and-honey/abudaraho] In the 15th century, Martino da Como describes the production of bottarga by salting then smoking to dry it.
[src:apples-and-honey/abudaraho] Bottarga is made chiefly from the roe pouch of grey mullet.
[src:apples-and-honey/abudaraho] Sometimes it is prepared from Atlantic bluefin tuna (*bottarga di tonno rosso*) or yellowfin tuna.
[src:apples-and-honey/abudaraho] It is massaged by hand to eliminate air pockets, then dried and cured in sea salt for a few weeks.
[src:apples-and-honey/abudaraho] Formerly, it was generally coated in beeswax to preserve it, as it still is in Greece and Egypt.
[src:apples-and-honey/abudaraho] Orange and molded in wax or vacuum sealed, Tunisian bottarga is made from mullet eggs and is known as a sought-after product.
[src:apples-and-honey/abudaraho] Initially a feature of the Judeo-Tunisian cuisine, it was introduced in Tunisia by Jews from Constantinople during Ottoman rule, as early as the 16th century.
[src:apples-and-honey/abudaraho] Bottarga is produced in the Port Said area.
[src:apples-and-honey/abudaraho] In Greece, it is called *avgotaraxo* or *avgotaracho* (Greek: αβγοτάραχο-αυγοτάραχο) and is produced primarily from the flathead mullet caught in Greek lagoons.
[src:apples-and-honey/abudaraho] The whole mature ovaries are removed from the fish, washed with water, salted with natural sea salt, dried under the sun, and sealed in melted beeswax.
[src:apples-and-honey/abudaraho] Avgotaracho Messolonghiou, made from fish caught in the Messolonghi-Etoliko Lagoons, is a European and Greek protected designation of origin, one of the few seafood products with a PDO.
[src:apples-and-honey/abudaraho] In Italy, it is made from bluefin tuna in Sicily, and from flathead mullet in Sardinia, where it is called Sardinian *butàriga*.
[src:apples-and-honey/abudaraho] Its culinary properties may be compared to those of dry anchovies, although it is much more expensive.
[src:apples-and-honey/abudaraho] Often, it is served with olive oil or lemon juice as an appetizer accompanied by bread or crostini.
[src:apples-and-honey/abudaraho] Bottarga is produced in Mauritania and Senegal.
[src:apples-and-honey/abudaraho] In Turkey, bottarga is made from grey mullet roe.
[src:apples-and-honey/abudaraho] It is produced in Dalyan, on the southwestern coast of Turkey, from the mature fish migrating from Lake Köyceğiz.
[src:apples-and-honey/abudaraho] There are various small producers elsewhere.
[src:apples-and-honey/abudaraho] For example, bottarga from Atlantic cod (*Gadus morhua*) is produced in northern Norway, where it is air-dried.
[src:apples-and-honey/adams-pearmain] '**Adams Pearmain**', also called '**Adam's Parmane**', is a cultivar of apple.
[src:apples-and-honey/adams-pearmain] It was introduced to the Horticultural Society of London in 1826 by Robert Adams, under the name '**Norfolk Pippin**'.
[src:apples-and-honey/adams-pearmain] The fruit is large, varying from two and a half inches to three inches high, and about the same in breadth at the widest part.
[src:apples-and-honey/adams-pearmain] It is pearmain-shaped, very even, and regularly formed.
[src:apples-and-honey/adams-pearmain] The skin is pale yellow tinged with green, and covered with delicate russet on the shaded side; but deep yellow tinged with red, and delicately streaked with livelier red on the side facing the sun.
[src:apples-and-honey/adams-pearmain] The flesh is reddish, crisp, juicy, rich, and sugary, with an agreeable and pleasantly perfumed flavor.
[src:apples-and-honey/adams-pearmain] This Cultivar is a sibling of Reinette de Hollande, a hybrid between Reinette Franche’ and ‘Reinette des Carmes.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] In Levantine cuisine, kibbeh is made by pounding bulgur wheat together with meat into a fine paste and forming it into ovoid shapes, with toasted pine nuts and spices.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] It may also be layered and cooked on a tray, deep-fried, grilled, or served raw.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] The Syrian city of Aleppo can lay claim to at least 17 types of kibbeh.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] In Mesopotamian cuisine, versions with rice or farina are found.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] Outside of Lebanon and Syria, versions are found in Cyprus, Egypt, Israel, Palestine, the Persian Gulf, Armenia, and Turkey, and among Assyrian people.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] It is also found throughout Latin American countries that received substantial numbers of immigrants from the Levant during the late 19th and early 20th centuries, as well as parts of North America.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] The modern word *kibbeh* (كبة) is derived from the Arabic root k-b-b (ك-ب-ب).
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] The use of *kubbeh* to designate stuffed food may have also been derived from the Akkadian language *kubbu*.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] The 10th century cookbook by Ibn Sayyar al-Warraq referred to meatballs as *kubab* (singular *kubba*).
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] As noted by food historian Nawal Nasrallah, the earliest mention of modern kibbeh, made with a filled shell of ground meat and grains, is in the 18th century work *Taj al-'Arus min Jawahir al-Qamus*.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] The text describes it as a disk of ground meat and rice flour made by the people of "al-Sham" (the Levant).
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] American Methodist missionary William McClure Thomson noted in his memoirs during his 1847 visit to Lebanon that kibbeh, then made by crushing wheat in mortar and pestle, was very popular.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] He described it as "the national dish of the Arabs", despite its association with the Levant.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] Swedish Orientalist Jacob Berggren described 8 types of kibbeh in his 1844 dictionary, and also mentioned a proverb about its social importance: "[...], without our koubbé, we would all have died".
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] The 1885 Beirut cookbook *Ustadh al-Tabbakhin* by author Khalil Khattar Sarkis provided 15 kibbeh recipes, including recipes for *kibbeh labaniyyeh*, *kiyyeh bil siniyyeh*, *kibbeh mashwiyyeh*, among others.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] The *Comparative Encyclopedia of Aleppo* by Syrian author Khayr al-Din al-Asadi (completed in 1971, published posthumously in 1981) described 58 different kinds of *kibbeh*.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] Kibbeh labaniyeh (Arabic: كبة لبنية) is a variant of kibbeh cooked in a yoghurt sauce and served over rice.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] *kibbeh mishwiyyeh* (Arabic: كبة مشوية) is kibbeh that is grilled rather than fried.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] In Lebanon, meatless versions of kibbeh exist, and are sometimes called "poor man's kibbe".
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] The stuffing is made with onions, walnuts, and wheat.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] *Kibbet samak*, made using fish, is popular among Sunni Muslims in North Lebanon.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] Potato *kibbeh* is a variation of kibbeh in which potato is mixed with the bulgur.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] It is often assembled in three layers: a potato layer, followed by the meat filling, then another potato layer on top.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] Author Claudia Roden describes it as an "oriental shepherd's pie." It is especially popular in Lebanon.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] The city of Aleppo, Syria, is known for its many varieties of *kibbe*.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] *Kibbeh sajiyeh* (Arabic: كبة صاجية) is kibbeh shaped into a thin disk with a meat filling that is traditionally dipped in a yogurt sauce.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] A Syrian soup known as *kubbi kishk* consists of *kubbi* ("torpedoes" or "footballs") in a yogurt (*kishk*) and butter broth with stewed cabbage leaves.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] Another soup, known as *kibbeh hamda*, consists of chicken stock with vegetables (usually leeks, celery, turnips and courgettes), lemon juice and garlic, with small *kibbeh* made with ground rice as dumplings.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] In the Syrian Jewish diaspora this dish is popular both for Pesach and as the pre-fast meal on the day before Yom Kippur.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] Among Kurdish Jews, there is a kubba soup flavored with aromatic thyme leaves during winter.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] In Turkey, kibbeh is called *içli köfte*.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] The outside shell can be made without or with tomato paste in different recipes.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] In Egypt, *kibbeh* is referred to as *kobeba* (Egyptian Arabic: كبيبة).
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] Seafood variations of kobeba exist, such as shrimp kobeba, popular in Port Said.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] Brazilian *quibe* is sometimes stuffed with Catupiry or another variety of *requeijão*, a sauce resembling ricotta and cream cheese.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] Most Brazilian *quibe* uses only ground beef, but other variations use tahini, *carne de soja* (texturized soy protein), *seitan* (Japanese wheat gluten-based meat substitute) or tofu (soybean curd) as stuffing.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] In the Brazilian state of Acre, a variation of *quibe* called *quibe de arroz* (rice kibbeh) is made with a rice flour breading.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] It was created by Arab immigrants to Brazil who had no access to wheat in the remote Amazon region of Brazil.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] On Colombia's Caribbean coast, most local variations of the dish use ground beef instead of lamb, but the original recipe, or one with a mixture of beef and lamb, can be found served by the large Lebanese and Syrian population of the area.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] The dish has acquired almost vernacular presence and is frequently served in social occasions at both Arab and non-Arab households.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] When served as an adopted local dish, it is offered often as a starter along with other regional specialties, including empanadas, deditos and carimañolas.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] The Dominican version was brought to the Dominican Republic by Lebanese immigrants.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] Some regional Syrian and Lebanese dishes combine *kibbeh* with elements taken from Latin American cuisine; for example, it is typical of Syrian Mexicans to eat traditional kibbeh with salsa verde.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] Kibbeh is considered by many to be a difficult dish to prepare, and as such, the quality of kibbeh is considered to be a benchmark for the skill of a cook in Iraq and the Levant.
[src:apples-and-honey/adom-kubbeh] Numerous mentions of kibbeh can be found in Aleppo Arabic folk proverbs.
[src:apples-and-honey/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu has large apples, weighing from 250 to 300 grams.
[src:apples-and-honey/aia-ilu] It is juicy, bittersweet, and has a weak aroma.
[src:apples-and-honey/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu is grown in nurseries, but is not widely propagated.
[src:apples-and-honey/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu has low scab resistance and is resistant to powdery mildew.
[src:apples-and-honey/airlie-red-flesh] Oregon apple with bright pink flesh and speckled green skin.
[src:apples-and-honey/airlie-red-flesh] The **Airlie Red Flesh**, (also known as the **Hidden Rose** or the **Mountain Rose**), is a cultivar of domesticated apple.
[src:apples-and-honey/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh tree will grow to a height of 4 meters (13 ft) to 5 meters (16 ft), and starts to fruit after about 4 years of growing.
[src:apples-and-honey/airlie-red-flesh] Airlie Red Flesh fruits are medium-sized, often small.
[src:apples-and-honey/airlie-red-flesh] The flavour of an Airlie Red Flesh apple has a balance of sweetness and tartness.
[src:apples-and-honey/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh apple has dark red flesh and a crisp texture.
[src:apples-and-honey/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh apple tends to ripen in late September.
[src:apples-and-honey/akane-apple] '**Akane'**, also known as '**Tokyo Rose'**, '**Tohoku No.3'** and '**Prime Red'**, is a Japanese cultivar of domesticated apple, that according to Orange Pippin is one of the best early season apples.
[src:apples-and-honey/akane-apple] 'Akane' was developed by the Morika Experimental Station of Japan sometime between 1900 and 1949, by crossing a Jonathan apple with a Worcester Pearmain, and was introduced to the United States in 1937, where it is very popular.
[src:apples-and-honey/akane-apple] 'Akane' is of moderately good disease resistance, best at warm climates but tolerates cold also.
[src:apples-and-honey/akane-apple] It flowers mid-late season, and should be harvested early-mid season.
[src:apples-and-honey/akane-apple] It is self-sterile and needs to be cross pollinated.
[src:apples-and-honey/akane-apple] It produces heavy crop of variable sized fruits, usually more to the smaller side, but good sized apples can be obtained by thinning.
[src:apples-and-honey/akane-apple] 'Akane' carries the fruit shape of the English 'Worcester Pearmain', and the unusually good balanced flavor of the 'Jonathan'.
[src:apples-and-honey/akane-apple] Shape ranges from flattened to heart-shaped.
[src:apples-and-honey/akane-apple] Fruits have a very good flavor, a blend of sweet and sharp, preferable for eating, keeps shape in cooking.
[src:apples-and-honey/akane-apple] Flesh color is white, with a yellow tinge.
[src:apples-and-honey/akane-apple] The apple is crisp, but not too dense; it is easy to eat.
[src:apples-and-honey/akane-apple] The fruit keeps fresh for about one week.
[src:apples-and-honey/apples-and-honey] Ancient Israelites likely did not eat apples and honey, since apples were not cultivated in the Levant at the time.
[src:apples-and-honey/apples-and-honey] Honey from wild bees is attested in the Bible and archaeologists have discovered an apiary from the 10th century BCE in Israel.
[src:apples-and-honey/apples-and-honey] However, boiled fruit syrups, such as date honey, were the more common form of honey at the time.
[src:apples-and-honey/apples-and-honey] The first known connection between apples and Rosh Hashanah is in the prayer book *Machzor Vitry*, written in 11th-century CE France.
[src:apples-and-honey/apples-and-honey] The first known mention of apples and honey being eaten on Rosh Hashanah comes from the 14th-century legal work *Arba'ah Turim*, which states that German Jews ate apples and honey in order to bring sweetness into the New Year.
[src:apples-and-honey/apples-and-honey] A contemporary of the author of *Arba'ah Turim*, Alexander Suslin, in his book *Sefer Ha'agudah*, attributes the custom to the Geonim.
[src:apples-and-honey/apples-and-honey] Apples and honey consists of raw apples sliced and served with a separate dish of honey.
[src:apples-and-honey/apples-and-honey] A blessing is said in Hebrew over the apples and honey, to ask for a "Sweet New Year", and the apple is then dipped into the honey and eaten.
[src:apples-and-honey/apples-and-honey] Dipping apples in honey is a minhag and is not dictated by the Tanakh or the Talmud.
[src:apples-and-honey/apples-and-honey] Ahead of Rosh Hashanah in English-speaking Ashkenazic schools, young schoolchildren learn the "dip the apple in the honey" song (to the tune of Oh My Darling, Clementine).
